Exponential Functions

So far we have seen how to evaluate equations of the form \(y = a^n\) when \(n\) is rational. We can see what happens for the case where \(n\) is real by examining the graph of exponential functions. An exponential function is a function of the form \(y = a^x\), here notice that the exponent varies with \(y\). We show in the figure below the graphs of \((0.5)^x, (0.3)^x,1^x,2^x\) and \(3^x\).

We can see that if \(a>b>0\) then \[ a^x>b^x\quad \text{if}\ x>0\qquad\qquad\text{and}\qquad\qquad a^x<b^x\quad \text{if}\ x<0 \]

 

\({\bf y=a^x}\) for various values of \({\bf a}\).

The most important and widely used exponential function has the particular base \(e= 2.7182818\dots\). We will discuss this in more detail in the next section. Note that the approximate value of \(e\) is stored in most calculators. Although all functions of the form \(a^x\) are called exponential functions we usually refer to \(e^x\) as the exponential function.
